@ThinkingandTinkering Good day mate. Hand pumping for linear pump because it's much cheaper, simple and smaller in design as well as easy to metered, slighty pressurized to enter the system, such as in oil and hydraulic servicing equipment for example. But if you have to pump for much larger volume and faster, circular is more relax, such as radiator water pump. Perhaps water hand pumps that utilized both principle is good analogy.

For machinery it depends on applications and other factors, either to pressurize, transfer volume, cost, etc. For example, air compressor normally convert to linear because the design is simple to create higher pressure and it can use mechanical advantage as leverage for much higher torque, so we can use smaller engine for it. Turbine engine is good example of how complicated it would be if we using circular motion to create higher pressure for air. To achieve the same pressure ratio, it will be much expensive and complicated design.

Of course, my explanation is only for simple design.
